    solution_text_english: "Difference between soap and detergent: Soap: (1) Sodium or potassium salts of long chain carboxylic acids. Example: C₁₇H₃₅COONa. (2) Made from vegetable oils. (3) Biodegradable - environment friendly. (4) Do not form lather in hard water forming insoluble salts. Detergent: (1) Salts of long chain sulfonic acids. (2) Made from petroleum products. (3) Some are non-biodegradable. (4) Form lather even in hard water. Hard water problem: Hard water contains Ca²⁺ and Mg²⁺ ions. Soap reacts with them forming insoluble salts: 2C₁₇H₃₅COONa + CaCl₂ → (C₁₇H₃₅COO)₂Ca↓ + 2NaCl. This precipitate (scum) does not form lather and deposits on clothes. Detergents do not form such salts, hence effective in hard water.",
